5.3 pH and Phosphorus Availability
P Availability vs pH
• Acid soils (pH < 5.5): Fe³n and Al³n abundant ® strong P fixation as FePOn and AlPOn ® P
unavailable
• Neutral soils (pH 6–7): Minimum P fixation ® MAXIMUM P availability
• Alkaline soils (pH > 7.5): Ca²n abundant ® CaHPOn, Can(POn)n precipitation ® P unavailable
Liming acid soil to pH 6–6.5 is the single most effective way to improve P availability.
Mycorrhizal fungi extend root surface area by 100–1000× ® dramatically improve P uptake in P-poor soils.
5.4 Phosphorus and Eutrophication
P is the limiting nutrient in most freshwater lakes. Even small additions of P (from agriculture, detergents,
sewage) cause massive algal blooms ® eutrophication ® DO depletion ® fish kills ® dead zones. The critical P
threshold for eutrophication in lakes = 0.02 mg/L total P.
