7. UGC NET Pattern MCQs with Explanations
Q1. Which clay mineral is responsible for the shrink-swell behaviour of Black Cotton Soils?
(a) Kaolinite
(b) Illite
(c) Montmorillonite (Smectite)
(d) Chlorite
4 Answer: (c)
Explanation: Montmorillonite (smectite) is a 2:1 expanding clay mineral with very high surface area (600–800 m²/g)
and CEC (80–120 cmol/kg). It absorbs large amounts of water between layers ® swells. On drying ® shrinks
dramatically. This creates the cracking and swelling behaviour of Black Cotton Soils (Vertisols) in Maharashtra,
Karnataka, and MP.
Q2. A crop residue with C:N ratio of 80:1 is incorporated into soil. What will happen to soil mineral
nitrogen in the short term?
(a) Net mineralisation – mineral N increases
(b) Net immobilisation – mineral N decreases as microbes consume it
(c) No change – C:N has no effect on N dynamics
(d) Denitrification – Nn is produced
4 Answer: (b)
Explanation: C:N > 30 ® net N immobilisation. Microbes need N to decompose the high-carbon material. They
consume available soil mineral N (NHnn, NOnn) ® temporary N deficiency for crops. Farmers should avoid
incorporating fresh straw before planting; allow partial decomposition first.
Q3. The process of conversion of ammonium (NHnn) to nitrate (NOnn) in soil is called:
(a) Ammonification
(b) Denitrification
(c) Nitrification
(d) Nitrogen fixation
4 Answer: (c)
Explanation: Nitrification is a two-step aerobic process: Step 1: NHnn ® NOnn (by Nitrosomonas); Step 2: NOnn
® NOnn (by Nitrobacter). It requires oxygen, optimal pH 6–8, and temperature 25–30°C. NOnn is mobile and can
leach to groundwater or be lost by denitrification.
Q4. Which of the following is the largest active flux in the global carbon cycle?
(a) Fossil fuel combustion (~10.5 Pg C/yr)
(b) Gross Primary Productivity – GPP (~120 Pg C/yr)
(c) Ocean uptake (~2.5 Pg C/yr)
(d) Land use change (~1.5 Pg C/yr)
4 Answer: (b)
Explanation: GPP (photosynthesis by all plants and phytoplankton) is the largest flux at ~120 Pg C/yr. Fossil fuel
combustion (~10.5 Pg C/yr), though the primary driver of rising COn, is much smaller than the natural biological
fluxes. However, natural fluxes are roughly balanced; it is the human addition that causes net increase.
Q5. Phosphorus availability in soil is maximum at pH:
(a) 4–5
(b) 5–6
