(c) 6–7
(d) 8–9
4 Answer: (c)
Explanation: At pH 6–7: Fe/Al phosphate precipitation is minimal AND Ca-phosphate precipitation is minimal. Below
pH 5.5: Al³n and Fe³n fix P as insoluble phosphates. Above pH 7.5: Ca²n precipitates P as CaHPOn, Can(POn)n.
This is why liming acid soil to pH 6–6.5 is the most effective P management strategy.
Q6. The CLAW hypothesis in the sulphur cycle relates to:
(a) Coal combustion causing acid rain
(b) DMS produced by phytoplankton acting as cloud condensation nuclei and influencing climate
(c) Sulphate reduction in marine sediments producing HnS
(d) Lime treatment of acid mine drainage
4 Answer: (b)
Explanation: The CLAW hypothesis (Charlson, Lovelock, Andreae, Warren, 1987) proposes a climate feedback loop:
warmer climate ® more phytoplankton ® more DMS ® oxidised to HnSOn aerosol ® more cloud condensation
nuclei ® brighter clouds ® more solar reflection ® cooling. A negative feedback (self-regulating) mechanism,
though its strength is debated.
Q7. Which organism is responsible for the ANAEROBIC AMMONIUM OXIDATION (anammox) reaction?
(a) Nitrosomonas europaea
(b) Pseudomonas denitrificans
(c) Planctomycetes (e.g., Brocadia anammoxidans)
(d) Rhizobium leguminosarum
4 Answer: (c)
Explanation: Anammox (anaerobic ammonium oxidation) is carried out by Planctomycetes bacteria, principally
Brocadia anammoxidans. Reaction: NHnn + NOnn ® Nn + 2HnO. It requires NO anaerobic conditions and is
responsible for ~50% of marine Nn production. It is also used in wastewater treatment (SHARON-ANAMMOX
process).
Q8. The biogeochemical cycle that LACKS a significant gaseous phase is:
(a) Carbon cycle
(b) Nitrogen cycle
(c) Phosphorus cycle
(d) Sulphur cycle
4 Answer: (c)
Explanation: The phosphorus cycle is a SEDIMENTARY cycle – it moves from rocks (apatite) through weathering to
soil and water, through organisms, and back to sediments. There is no significant volatile phosphorus compound (no
PHn gas at scale). This makes P cycling very slow and explains why P is often limiting in ecosystems.
